TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Formation of Prosociality: Causal Evidence on the Role of Social Environment
AU  - Kosse, Fabian
AU  - Deckers, Thomas
AU  - Pinger, Pia
AU  - Schildberg-Hörisch, Hannah
AU  - Falk, Armin
Y1  - 2019/05/14
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/704386
DO  - 10.1086/704386
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 434
EP  - 467
VL  - 128
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This study presents evidence on the role of social environment for the formation of prosociality. We show that socioeconomic status (SES) as well as intensity of mother-child interaction and mothers? prosocial attitudes are related to elementary school children?s prosociality. We also present evidence on a randomly assigned variation of the social environment, providing children with a mentor for 1 year. Our data reveal a significant and persistent increase in prosociality in the treatment relative to the control group. Moreover, enriching the social environment closes the prosociality gap between low- and high-SES children. A mediation analysis suggests that prosociality develops in response to prosocial role models and intense social interactions.
AB  - This study presents evidence on the role of social environment for the formation of prosociality. We show that socioeconomic status (SES) as well as intensity of mother-child interaction and mothers? prosocial attitudes are related to elementary school children?s prosociality. We also present evidence on a randomly assigned variation of the social environment, providing children with a mentor for 1 year. Our data reveal a significant and persistent increase in prosociality in the treatment relative to the control group. Moreover, enriching the social environment closes the prosociality gap between low- and high-SES children. A mediation analysis suggests that prosociality develops in response to prosocial role models and intense social interactions.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/704386
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/704386
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Moving the Goalposts
AU  - Ely, Jeffrey C.
AU  - Szydlowski, Martin
Y1  - 2019/05/14
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/704387
DO  - 10.1086/704387
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 468
EP  - 506
VL  - 128
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study information as an incentive device in a dynamic moral hazard framework. An agent works on a task of uncertain difficulty, modeled as the duration of required effort. The principal knows the task difficulty and provides information over time. The optimal mechanism features moving goalposts: an initial disclosure makes the agent sufficiently optimistic that the task is easy. If the task is indeed difficult, the agent is told this only after working long enough to put the difficult task within reach. The agent then completes the difficult task even though he never would have chosen to at the outset.
AB  - We study information as an incentive device in a dynamic moral hazard framework. An agent works on a task of uncertain difficulty, modeled as the duration of required effort. The principal knows the task difficulty and provides information over time. The optimal mechanism features moving goalposts: an initial disclosure makes the agent sufficiently optimistic that the task is easy. If the task is indeed difficult, the agent is told this only after working long enough to put the difficult task within reach. The agent then completes the difficult task even though he never would have chosen to at the outset.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/704387
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/704387
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Political Booms, Financial Crises
AU  - Herrera, Helios
AU  - Ordoñez, Guillermo
AU  - Trebesch, Christoph
Y1  - 2019/05/20
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/704544
DO  - 10.1086/704544
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 507
EP  - 543
VL  - 128
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Political booms, measured by the rise in governments? popularity, predict financial crises above and beyond better known early warning indicators, such as credit booms. This predictive power, however, only holds in emerging economies. We argue that governments in developing countries have stronger incentives to ?ride? unsound credit booms in order to boost their popularity, rather than implementing corrective policies that could prevent crises but are politically costly. We provide evidence of the relevance of this mechanism, partly by constructing a new cross-country data set on government popularity based on opinion polls.
AB  - Political booms, measured by the rise in governments? popularity, predict financial crises above and beyond better known early warning indicators, such as credit booms. This predictive power, however, only holds in emerging economies. We argue that governments in developing countries have stronger incentives to ?ride? unsound credit booms in order to boost their popularity, rather than implementing corrective policies that could prevent crises but are politically costly. We provide evidence of the relevance of this mechanism, partly by constructing a new cross-country data set on government popularity based on opinion polls.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/704544
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/704544
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Political Economy of Weak Treaties
AU  - Battaglini, Marco
AU  - Harstad, Bård
Y1  - 2019/05/23
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/704610
DO  - 10.1086/704610
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 544
EP  - 590
VL  - 128
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In recent decades, democratic countries have negotiated hundreds of international treaties and agreements. This paper analyzes the equilibrium design of treaties negotiated by political incumbents seeking reelection. We show that incumbents are prone to negotiate treaties that are ?weak,? in that they may or may not be complied with: this makes it possible to differentiate the alternative candidates in a way that favors the incumbent. We also show that political economy considerations lead to overambitious treaties that rely too much on technology instead of sanctions to motivate compliance. Our theory can rationalize several puzzles associated with treaties.
AB  - In recent decades, democratic countries have negotiated hundreds of international treaties and agreements. This paper analyzes the equilibrium design of treaties negotiated by political incumbents seeking reelection. We show that incumbents are prone to negotiate treaties that are ?weak,? in that they may or may not be complied with: this makes it possible to differentiate the alternative candidates in a way that favors the incumbent. We also show that political economy considerations lead to overambitious treaties that rely too much on technology instead of sanctions to motivate compliance. Our theory can rationalize several puzzles associated with treaties.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/704610
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/704610
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

